## Statement of soundness and completeness

Recall that $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n\vdash \phi$ means that there is a proof in our natural deduction system for classical logic with premises among $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n$ and with conclusion $\phi$.

And recall that $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \vDash \phi$ means that any model which interprets all of the symbols in these formulas is such that if $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n$ are true on the model, then $\phi$ is true on the model.

It turns out that these two notions extensionally align. This alignment is separated into two parts which are given the following traditional names:

- *The Soundness Theorem*: if $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \vdash \phi$, then $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \vDash \phi$.

- *The Completeness Theorem*: if $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \vDash \phi$, then $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \vdash \phi$.

The proof of the Soundness Theorem is not difficult. To give an illustration, consider the argument for $Fa\vdash \exists \; x \; Fx$ which goes through one application of existential introduction. To check that $Fa\vDash \exists \; x \; Fx$, one just notes that if $\mathcal{M}\models Fa$ then by the existential clause of Tarski's definition of truth in a model, we have $\mathcal{M}\models \exists \;x \; Fx$.

The proof of the Completeness Theorem is harder. This is the topic of metalogic, which is the next course after a course like this one.

It is worth highlighting a specific case of the Soundness and Completeness Theorem, namely the case where there are no premises. In this case, they read:

- *The Soundness Theorem*: if $\vdash \phi$, then $\vDash \phi$.

- *The Completeness Theorem*: if $\vDash \phi$, then $\vdash \phi$.

Hence, the Soundness Theorem says that if $\phi$ is provable from no extra hypotheses or premises, then $\phi$ is true in absolutely all models. And the Completeness Theorem says that if $\phi$ is true in absolutely all models, then $\phi$ is provable from no extra hypotheses or premises. Often a "tautology" is defined in terms of one of these two notions, and the Soundness and Completeness Theorem tell us that they align.

Another useful case of the Soundness and Completeness Theorem is when the conclusion is falsum. In this case the Soundness and Completeness Theorem together imply each of the following biconditionals:

1. $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \vdash \bot$ iff $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \vDash \bot$

2. $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \nvdash \bot$ iff $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \nvDash \bot$

3. $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n$ does not derive a contradiction iff there is a model of $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n$ which is not a model of a contradiction.

4. $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n$ does not derive a contradiction iff there is a model of $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n$

In this, 1 is just a literal restatement of the Soundness and Completeness Theorem as a single biconditional. And 2 just results by negating both sides of the biconditional in 1. And 3 results from 2 by recalling that ex falso rule makes $\bot$ a stand-in for any contradiction. And 4 results from 3 by noting that no model is a model of a contradiction. This fourth and last formulation can be then expressed as: deductive consistency of the premises is the same as the premises having a model. This is important because it ties a formal feature of a deductive system (deductive consistency) directly to the existence of a model. Indeed, it is in this formulation that the Completeness Theorems is usually proven.

A final word on notation. A logic is, in general, a collection of formulas together with a deductive system and a semantics. For instance, in a first logic class, one learned propositional logic together with some deductive system and the semantics was truth-tables. In this class we have learned predicate logic together with a deductive system and the semantics was models. One says that a logic is *sound* if the Soundness Theorem holds for the pair consisting of its deductive system and semantics. And one says that logic is *complete* if the Completeness Theorem holds for the pair consisting of its deductive system and semantics. For instance, intuitionistic logic is sound but incomplete since law of the excluded middle is valid, but yet it is not provable in intuitionistic logic. Usually the terms "sound" and "complete" are not capitalized when they are used as adjectives for a logic, but they are capitalized when they are used to name theorems, e.g. "The Soundness Theorem" and "The Completeness Theorem."

