## Useful reformuations of soundness

Soundness is most useful in its contrapositive form:

- *The Soundness Theorem*: if $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \nvDash \phi$ then $\phi_1, \ldots, \phi_n \nvdash \phi$.

That is, it is saying that if one has found at least one model where the premises are true and the conclusion false, then there cannot possibly be a proof of that conclusion from the premises. The Soundness Theorem is presuambly explanatory of why we think that we should stop looking for a proof once a counterexample has been found. It might well be part of why we think that a counterexample shows that something must be awry with any purported proof of the conclusion from the premises.

That said, there are lots of models out there. And maybe a single counterexample is less significant to the extent that it is unnatural or ad-hoc or not faithful to the target phenomena.
But some constraints on e.g. naturality will be formalizable as further premises, and then what should really be evaluated is the argument supplemented by this further premise.


